---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Morocco Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/morocco/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Spain for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/spain' },
  { title: 'Portugal for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/portugal' },
  { title: 'Insurance with Pre-existing Conditions', href: '/insurance-for/pre-existing-conditions' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'moroccoFit', header: 'Morocco Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$380-520/mo', moroccoFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$450-640/mo', moroccoFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$340-480/mo', moroccoFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$360-500/mo', moroccoFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'SAHAM Assurance', entryAge: '65', renewal: '75', monthlyFrom: 'MAD 800-2,000/mo', moroccoFit: 'Good (Local)' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$350-520', annual: '$4,200-6,240' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: '$480-700', annual: '$5,760-8,400' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: '$650-950', annual: '$7,800-11,400' },
  { category: 'Moroccan Private Insurance', monthly: 'MAD 600-2,500', annual: 'MAD 7,200-30,000' },
  { category: 'Out-of-pocket (typical)', monthly: 'Low', annual: '$500-2,000' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Morocco | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Morocco. Visa options, private healthcare, costs, and coverage for expats 70+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Morocco"
  subheadline="Morocco offers African adventure with French-influenced healthcare, affordable living, and easy access from Europe—ideal for adventurous retirees."
  heroImage="/images/countries/morocco-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Morocco</h2>
  <p>
    Morocco offers a unique retirement proposition: the exotic appeal of North Africa combined with French colonial infrastructure, affordable costs, and proximity to Europe. For seniors seeking adventure without sacrificing healthcare access, Morocco provides an intriguing alternative to standard European destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Marrakech attracts the most retirees with its famous medina, riads, and established expat community. Essaouira offers a laid-back coastal alternative. Casablanca provides modern urban amenities and the best healthcare. Rabat, the capital, offers a quieter sophisticated environment. Tangier is popular with Europeans for its proximity to Spain.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> French widely spoken; Arabic official; English limited</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Good private hospitals in major cities</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> $1,200-2,000/month comfortable lifestyle</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Mediterranean coast; desert interior; varies widely</li>
      <li><strong>Europe access:</strong> 3-hour flight from Paris/London</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Morocco's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Morocco's healthcare system reflects its French heritage, with quality private clinics in major cities. For seniors, the private sector provides good care, though complex cases may warrant evacuation to Europe.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    Private clinics in Casablanca, Rabat, and Marrakech offer French-influenced care:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clinique Internationale (Casablanca):</strong> Best equipped; international standard</li>
    <li><strong>Clinique Dar Salam (Casablanca):</strong> Modern facility; various specialties</li>
    <li><strong>Polyclinique du Sud (Marrakech):</strong> Main private option; expat-familiar</li>
    <li><strong>Clinique Agdal (Rabat):</strong> Good private hospital</li>
    <li><strong>CHU (University Hospitals):</strong> Public but with private wings</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Healthcare costs are very affordable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP consultation:</strong> MAD 200-400 ($20-40)</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> MAD 400-800 ($40-80)</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital day (private):</strong> MAD 1,500-4,000 ($150-400)</li>
    <li><strong>MRI:</strong> MAD 2,000-4,000 ($200-400)</li>
    <li><strong>Hip replacement:</strong> MAD 80,000-150,000 ($8,000-15,000)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>French as Medical Language</h3>
  <p>
    French is the language of Moroccan medicine. Doctors train in French, medical records are in French, and consultations often mix French and Arabic. English-speaking doctors exist in major cities but aren't universal.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Europe as Backup</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Morocco's proximity to Europe (3-hour flight to Paris, 1 hour to Madrid) means evacuation to world-class European hospitals is feasible for complex cases. Many insurers cover this. For seniors, this European safety net adds significant peace of mind.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Senior Retirees</h2>
  <p>
    Morocco doesn't have a formal retirement visa, but the straightforward residency process makes long-term stay accessible.
  </p>

  <h3>Tourist Entry + Residency Application</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Initial entry:</strong> 90 days visa-free (US, UK, EU citizens)</li>
    <li><strong>Residency application:</strong> Apply at local préfecture</li>
    <li><strong>Requirements:</strong> Proof of income/funds, accommodation, criminal record</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 1-year carte de séjour, renewable</li>
    <li><strong>No minimum income:</strong> Varies by préfecture; generally reasonable</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Residency Process</h3>
  <p>
    Unlike some countries, Morocco's residency is applied for after arrival:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Enter on tourist stamp (90 days)</li>
    <li>Find accommodation, get rental contract</li>
    <li>Apply at local préfecture for carte de séjour</li>
    <li>Provide bank statements, income proof, lease</li>
    <li>Receive 1-year residency card</li>
    <li>Renew annually; can apply for 10-year card after 5 years</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Health Insurance for Residency</h3>
  <p>
    Proof of health insurance may be requested for residency application. International or Moroccan insurance accepted.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Planning Your Morocco Retirement?"
    description="Get coverage that works in North Africa and Europe."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Morocco may require health insurance for residency, though enforcement varies. More importantly, insurance is practical necessity.
  </p>

  <h3>Why Insurance Matters in Morocco</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No public access:</strong> Moroccan public healthcare for citizens only</li>
    <li><strong>Private costs:</strong> Affordable but add up for extended care</li>
    <li><strong>Evacuation option:</strong> Europe evacuation provides safety net</li>
    <li><strong>Residency requirement:</strong> Some préfectures request proof</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Coverage Recommendations</h3>
  <p>
    For Morocco, ensure your policy includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Morocco coverage:</strong> Direct billing at major clinics</li>
    <li><strong>European coverage:</strong> For evacuation and complex care</li>
    <li><strong>Evacuation:</strong> Air ambulance to Europe if needed</li>
    <li><strong>Repatriation:</strong> Return to home country</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Providers for Morocco</h2>
  <p>
    These insurers work well for seniors in Morocco:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent choice with Africa/Europe combined coverage. Entry up to 74 with lifetime renewal. Evacuation to European hospitals included. Direct billing at Moroccan private clinics.
  </p>

  <h3>AXA Global</h3>
  <p>
    French company with strong Morocco presence. Good understanding of Francophone healthcare. Entry up to 74 with lifetime renewal. Natural fit for Morocco's French-influenced system.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to 79. Essential for seniors 75-79. Comprehensive worldwide coverage including Europe for complex care. Premium pricing but reliable.
  </p>

  <h3>Moroccan Local Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Companies like SAHAM, Wafa Assurance, and Atlanta offer local plans. Age limits typically 60-65. Affordable but Morocco-only coverage. French documentation. Can supplement with international evacuation coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Plans for Morocco"
    description="Find coverage spanning North Africa and Europe."
    buttonText="See Options →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for Morocco are moderate, with affordable local healthcare:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Moroccan Healthcare Affordability</h3>
  <p>
    Private healthcare in Morocco is very affordable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Routine visit:</strong> $20-40</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist consultation:</strong> $40-80</li>
    <li><strong>Dental work:</strong> 60-80% less than Europe</li>
    <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Generally affordable (import prices)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High deductible:</strong> Pay routine care out-of-pocket</li>
    <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> Africa + Europe sufficient (no worldwide)</li>
    <li><strong>Use local clinics:</strong> International clinic prices higher</li>
    <li><strong>Annual payment:</strong> 5-10% discount common</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Routine Care in Marrakech</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Patricia, 70, needs checkup and blood pressure medication.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Visits French-speaking doctor at Polyclinique du Sud. Consultation MAD 300 ($30), bloodwork MAD 500 ($50), 3-month medication MAD 400 ($40). Total: $120. Pays out-of-pocket.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Specialist in Casablanca</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Robert, 69, needs cardiologist consultation.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Sees specialist at Clinique Internationale Casablanca. Consultation + echo MAD 1,500 ($150). Cigna Global covers after deductible. Good quality; French-speaking care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Major Surgery in Morocco</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Carol, 72, needs hip replacement.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Surgery at Clinique Dar Salam Casablanca. Total MAD 100,000 ($10,000). Allianz Care covers after $2,500 deductible. Quality good; recovery in Morocco.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Complex Case Requiring Europe</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">James, 74, diagnosed with rare cancer.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Initial diagnosis in Casablanca. For complex treatment, BUPA Global arranges evacuation to Paris (3-hour flight). Treatment at Institut Gustave Roussy. €80,000 covered. Morocco for recovery, Europe for treatment.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: French-Speaking Challenge</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Susan, 68, speaks no French.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Finds English-speaking doctor through expat community (they exist in Marrakech). For hospital stay, hires translator. Workable but more effort than French-speaking destinations. Learning basic French recommended.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Senior Over 75</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">William, 77, wants adventurous retirement.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gets BUPA Global ($780/month). Carte de séjour approved. Lives in Essaouira; travels to Casablanca for medical needs. Knows Europe evacuation available for serious issues. Adventure with safety net.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak French?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">For healthcare, French is very helpful. Moroccan medical professionals train in French. English-speaking doctors exist in major cities but aren't guaranteed. Learning medical French or hiring a translator is recommended. Arabic is official but French dominates professional settings.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the residency process difficult?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Relatively straightforward but bureaucratic. Requirements vary by préfecture. Expect multiple visits, paperwork in French, and patience. Many expats hire a local "fixer" to navigate the process. Generally achievable within 90-day tourist period.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does Marrakech compare to Casablanca for healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Casablanca has the best hospitals (Clinique Internationale, Dar Salam). Marrakech has adequate private clinics but fewer specialists. For routine care, Marrakech is fine. For complex care or if you have ongoing conditions, Casablanca access is valuable.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">I'm 76—what are my options?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">BUPA Global accepts up to 79. Moroccan insurers typically cap at 60-65. At 76, BUPA Global (or similar) is your main option. The proximity to Europe provides additional security—evacuation flight to Paris is only 3 hours.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Morocco safe for seniors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Generally yes, especially in tourist areas. Morocco is stable by regional standards. Petty theft exists; traffic is chaotic. Major cities have established expat communities. Healthcare limitations are the main concern—ensure you have good insurance and European evacuation coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I fly to Spain for healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, easily. Tangier to Spain is a 35-minute ferry. Marrakech to Madrid is 1.5 hours by air. Many expats use Spanish private hospitals for complex care. Your insurance should cover Spain. This Europe proximity is a major Morocco advantage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Morocco?"
    description="Find coverage spanning Africa and Europe."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes. Moroccan residency requirements and healthcare capabilities change. Verify current requirements with Moroccan authorities. Consider learning French and connecting with the expat community in your target city.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
